node.text:
"When I became pregnant with my daughter, I was prepared for the numerous changes that pregnancy can have on your body; I'd been thoroughly warned about swollen ankles and an achy back," explains writer Caroline Chirichella. "What I didn't know was that the digestive system issues I experienced in the days after having my baby—constipation, diarrhea, and hemorrhoids—would continue long after I gave birth."
.
Here, we break down what you need to know before giving birth. Tap the link in bio for the full story 👆

Photo by Health on August 07, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Why do these bowel movement changes happen? The soreness and pain after childbirth can limit the ability to bear down and, therefore, the ability to go No. 2. Medication for postpartum pain can make your bowels slower, resulting in constipation. Your bowel movements greatly depend on the integrity of your pelvic floor, which just went through something major and needs time to recover. Health'.

Photo by Health on August 07, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Why do these bowel movement changes happen? Pelvic floor changes often result in constipation, which in turn causes hemorrhoids during and after birth. Progesterone levels are higher during pregnancy, which can slow down your entire GI tract. Health'.

May be an image of text that says 'Here's how doctors recommend treating these postpartum bowel issues: Hemorrhoids Increase dietary fiber and water intake Use stool softeners, hydrocortisone creams and suppositories, and sitz baths Constipation Eat a high-fiber diet and drink plenty of water Take fiber supplements, stool softeners, and/or a laxative Health'.

node.text:
#WorldBreastfeedingWeek part 2: These moms are sharing the realities of breastfeeding—that includes both the highs and the lows. 
.
@_meeksonthemove explains that while preparing for motherhood she didn’t realize just how much she should be preparing to breastfeed too: “I always knew I would be breast feeding my baby, so I guess I just blindly assumed it would come naturally. I didn't anticipate how difficult it could be for some,” she said. 
.
During the first few weeks, she wanted to quit. “From baby's poor latch that lead to sore, raw, bloody nipples, to rock hard engorged breasts the size of my baby's head, and around the clock cluster feeding, I literally cried every time it was time to feed my baby. I dreaded every moment of It. It honestly took everything in me not to give up, but I've wanted this for so long, that just wasn't an option.”
.
Remember that your feelings are valid, adds @thepeninsulamumma: “You are allowed to say that it’s a lot. It does not mean you are not grateful. It does not mean you do not love your child. It does not make you any less of an incredible mother. All it means is that you are human. That you are human like me. Because it’s a lot for me & I need you to know you are not alone in this bubble & that I promise you that one day soon, that bubble will burst just like I promise you that the sun will rise. And it WILL rise, just like you will. 🌞"
.
Tap the link in bio for the full story 👆

node.text:
#JenniferAniston recently revealed that she ended some relationships with people over their unwillingness to get vaccinated. "There's still a large group of people who are anti-vaxxers or just don't listen to the facts. It's a real shame," she said to our sister publication @instylemagazine. "I've just lost a few people in my weekly routine who have refused or did not disclose [their vaccination status], and it was unfortunate."
.
Now, @JenniferAniston is responding to criticism on her Instagram Stories over her comments, and clearing up some questions people have. She singled out a question from one commenter: "But if she's vaccinated, she's protected correct? Why be worried about unvaxxed around her?" 
.
Aniston's response: "Because if you have the [Delta] variant, you are still able to give it to me. I may get slightly sick but I will not be admitted to the hospital and or die. BUT I CAN give it to someone else who does not have the vaccine and whose health is compromised (or has a previous existing condition) - and therefore I would put their lives at risk. THAT is why I worry. We have to care about more than just ourselves here."
.
Aniston also said that she feels people have a "moral and professional obligation" to let people know their vaccination status. “It's tricky because everyone is entitled to their own opinion — but a lot of opinions don't feel based in anything except fear or propaganda," she said. Tap the link in bio for the full story 👆

node.text: Scratching your head over bruises you don't remember getting? Sometimes these black-and-blue marks pop up with little or no provocation, although clinicians say there's usually a perfectly good explanation or a treatable underlying cause. Here are some common reasons that you may be bruising easily—and what you can do about it. Tap the link in bio for the full story 👆

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Health on August 06, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says '9 Reasons You Bruise So Easily Health'.

Photo by Health on August 06, 2021. May be an image of text that says '1. Your skin is sun damaged Many years of sun exposure can weaken blood vessel walls, contributing to a type of bruising in older adults known as "actinic purpura" or "senile purpura"- unsightly purple patches that occur on the backs of the hands and forearms without much of a bump or injury. Health'.

Photo by Health on August 06, 2021. May be an image of text that says '2. Your blood platelet count is low If bruises seem to appear for no reason, it could signal you were born with a platelet disorder. Platelets are crucial because they help form clots to slow or halt bleeding. You can either have an insufficient number of platelets, or your platelets don't work normally. Health'.

Photo by Health on August 06, 2021. May be an image of text that says '3. You have a bleeding disorder Bruising in and of itself may not be a big deal. But when it's accompanied by other symptoms, ike nosebleeds, heavy periods, or excessive bleeding after surgery, then you might suspect something more than just accidental bruising. Health'.

Photo by Health on August 06, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says '4. Your liver is hurting If your liver is diseased or damaged, there may be fewer platelets circulating in your blood than you need for normal blood clotting, and that can cause you to bruise easily. Health'.

node.text:
#WorldBreastfeedingWeek part 1: These photos are vulnerable, honest, and powerful—and they were all published in the name of normalizing breastfeeding. “Why is it so taboo to do something that women were made to do,” said @zoeallamby. “Our bodies were literally designed to produce milk for and feed our babies.”
.
Each year, WBW has a theme. This year, two themes emerged. One is about how "breastfeeding contributes to the survival, health, and wellbeing of all," while the other focuses on the need to protect breastfeeding worldwide. That means making sure breastfeeding accommodations are made for nursing moms, and that they're not subjected to judgmental stares.
.
This is important, because breastfeeding in public is not always considered acceptable. Allamby described a negative experience she recently had in a doctor's waiting room with her daughter: "I started to [breastfeed] with her burp cloth covering her face and I couldn't help but notice the stares I got as I began to feed my baby. At first I thought I was being paranoid but I looked up and down several times and saw the repeated uncomfortable stares :/.”
.
"I’ve hid in bathroom stalls to feed my kids," added @terriannmichelle. I’ve covered up in the dead of summer in the blistering heat to the point that both baby and I were dripping sweat to try to stop others from 'having to see me feed my kid.'"
.
She offered some words of encouragement no matter what stage of the journey you’re at: “It’s not supposed to be easy. And you’re not a failure. It’s a marathon you could have never trained for.”
.
Tap the link in bio for the full story 👆

node.text:
This week's #WellnessWarriors feature is Alex Jenny (she/they), also known as The Drag Therapist, a clinical social worker who specializes in trauma recovery and gender identity. Jenny, a child of Chinese Vietnamese refugees, dedicates their work as a therapist and drag artist to “creating celebratory spaces that center trans people of color, specifically trans women and femmes.”
.
Inspired by their own mental health struggles, Jenny became a therapist to help others heal from trauma and systemic violence against BIPOC and LGBTQ+ individuals. “I found that this work keeps me accountable to the healing I need to do for myself and my communities,” Jenny tells Health. They post photos such as these to Instagram as an extension of their work, which includes resources on how to find an affirming therapist as an LGBTQ+ person of color and ways that certain traumas around identity can show up in everyday life and interactions.
.
Jenny is bold and unapologetic in her expressions of trans joy and happiness, even when people leave threatening messages and comments about her and her work. “[Trans] existence is proof that new worlds are possible,” Jenny says. “It means cultivating joy by any means necessary. Trans and gender nonconforming people have skills and resilience that everyone can learn from.” 
.
To learn more about Jenny’s work as an affirming therapist and how drag helps them explore and celebrate their identities, follow @alexjenny_.

node.text:
#SimoneBiles is redefining what strength means as a Black woman—and writer Jess Sims of @aneutrallife is explaining why that’s so important. 
.
“As a Black woman growing up in America, rest always felt like a foreign concept—not necessarily sleeping a full eight hours or taking naps, but real mental and emotional rest,” says Sims. So when Biles, one of the most decorated American gymnasts at only 24 years old, chose to withdraw from multiple events during the 2021 Olympic Games in Tokyo, it felt revolutionary. “It's time that Black women follow suit and start prioritizing our mental health, too.”
.
As Black women, we are taught to be strong, she explains. “Our mothers, cognizant of the harsh and often unfair world we were entering, taught us to prioritize everything but rest as an act of survival. But that so-called badge of honor—the ‘strong Black woman’ persona—may be doing us more harm than good.”
.
In a 2019 research article published in the Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences, researchers found that, in the face of racial discrimination, Black women opt to present a ‘superwoman’ front. “That means we suppress our emotions, instead choosing to portray ourselves as an image of strength and competence; it's our defense mechanism,” says Sims. “But being a ‘strong Black woman’ is both a coat of armor and a liability—it's an outward behavior that doesn't always show how we really feel.”
.
By stepping down, even just temporarily from the Olympic stage, Biles is working to rewrite what strength means in Black women. Tap the link in bio for the full story 👆 (📸: @matt.joe)
